The Burbank Early Childhood School playground and Barrington Elementary School Welcome Playground are reopening, but please be advised that playground equipment is not being cleaned or sanitized and residents who choose to use this equipment do so at their own risk.

If you choose to use our playgrounds:
* Wash hands or use hand sanitizer before and after use;
* Avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands;
* Keep your distance from other residents who are not part of your group (please remind children as well); and
* Stay home if you are sick or feeling unwell.

The remaining elementary school playgrounds are closed due to construction.

post_text: Racism permeates every area of society in our country, including schools. We are committed to making Upper Arlington Schools a place where All Means All, and every single student is welcomed, respected, supported and celebrated. We know there is a tremendous amount of work to be done to combat racism and support diversity, equity and inclusion in our schools, but our commitment will not be deterred. We are proud to collaborate with the City of Upper Arlington, Upper Arlington Police and many passionate community volunteers to continue to make our schools and community better places for everyone. #UAAllMeansAll
shared_text:
The City of Upper Arlington - Government
May 30 at 9:15 PM ·

Message from City Manager Steve Schoeny and Police Chief Steve Farmer
May 29, 2020

Racism exists and harms our country, our state, our region and Upper Arlington. When we see the deaths of George Floyd, Breonna Taylor and Ahmaud Arbery, it reminds us that our African American brothers and sisters in America have fears that we, as white men in Upper Arlington, don’t have. When any member of our American family feels afraid to be in America – when they are afraid to do the simplest of things that the rest of us take for granted – we should all be afraid.

One email won’t erase our historic and current racism. Changing laws alone won’t fix it. But that doesn’t mean that we don’t acknowledge it…

We are proud to collaborate with the City of Upper Arlington, Upper Arlington Police and many passionate community volunteers to continue to make our schools and community better places for everyone. #UAAllMeansAll

CONGRATULATIONS to the Class of 2020! We are excited to celebrate these seniors and their amazing accomplishments today!

The cars-only parade through the heart of UA sets off at 10 a.m. A couple of reminders for friends, family and neighbors celebrating our seniors this morning:

* Any Class of 2020 family members and friends who are not riding in the vehicle of the graduate may park along the route by 9:40 a.m and must remain parked for the duration of the parade. We strongly encourage that these spectators stay in their vehicles for the parade.

* Any neighbors along the route who wish to watch the parade outside of their homes should maintain an appropriate distance (at least 6 feet or more) from any other neighbors.

More details are available on our website at www.uaschools.org. THANK YOU for your support in helping us make this a safe and celebratory event for our seniors and their families! #GoBears #ServeLeadSucceed

Important information about the #UAHSClassof2020 cars-only parade! UA Schools and The City of Upper Arlington will be celebrating our seniors with a parade through the heart of UA on Sunday beginning at 10 a.m. Friends, family and community members may offer support from their own parked cars (or yards if they live along the parade route).

Please note that any Class of 2020 family members and friends who are not riding in the vehicle of the graduate may park along the route by 9:40 a.m and must remain parked for the duration of the parade. We strongly encourage that these spectators stay in their vehicles for the parade.

post_text:
Our teachers are creating some amazing distance learning opportunities for our students! This poem from one of our elementary learners - Jackson, a 5th grade student from Greensview Elementary School - has a great message for all of us:

"Bears stay alone, and right now, we have to, too. But the cub will stay with its family still, like you. The bear’s danger of cougars relates to our danger of getting sick. How bears still live their life away from others is an example of how we need to act to protect loved ones and others from getting sick from the virus.”

#StartWithHeart #ServeLeadSucceed

As part of their study of local history, third-grade students at Windermere are researching the history of their current school building. They are looking for any alumni and former staff members interested in sharing their memories of Windermere - especially between the years 1960 and 1990. If you're interested, please visit https://forms.gle/s8Fq7x1wFotHdPHD7 to share your information!

The students will share their findings at the open house and ceremonial groundbreaking celebrating the old and the new Windermere on Sunday, April 26. #BuildingOurFuture #ServeLeadSucceed #WholeLearning

post_text: A historic #WholeLearning experience for our students! The Kickin' It Live team is preparing to document a major milestone for the new Upper Arlington High School - the raising of the final steel beam, signed by students, staff and community members. These students walked the site today with our COO, Chris Potts, and the Ruscilli Construction Co., Inc. team to see firsthand the progress on the new high school! #BuildingOurFuture #ServeLeadSucceed

post_text: Congratulations to Wickliffe 5th grader Dillon on being selected as the winner of the inaugural Chris Collaros essay contest for the Progressive Education Network! Her beautifully written essay shares her experiences with community, compassion and civility at Wickliffe through the examples of Mr. Collaros, friendships and the Wickliffe Wolf Pack. #LoveOutLoud #ServeLeadSucceed #PEN
